          <h2 class="section-heading section-heading--no-em">Electrical questions, answered honestly.</h2>
          <p class="section-body">Before you book, here are the answers to what our customers ask most often.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-grid">
          <div class="faq-col">
            <div class="faq-item fade-up"><button type="button" class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false"><span>How much does an electrician cost in LA?</span><span class="faq-icon"><svg width="11" height="11" viewBox="0 0 12 12" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path d="M6 2v8M2 6h8"/></svg></span></button><div class="faq-answer"><p>We provide flat-rate quotes for all standard jobs before any work starts. Small jobs like outlet installation or fixture replacement are priced differently than panel upgrades or EV charger installs. Call or fill out the form for a specific quote.</p></div></div>
            <div class="faq-item fade-up"><button type="button" class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false"><span>Do I need a permit for electrical work?</span><span class="faq-icon"><svg width="11" height="11" viewBox="0 0 12 12" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path d="M6 2v8M2 6h8"/></svg></span></button><div class="faq-answer"><p>It depends on the scope. Simple replacements (outlet for outlet, fixture for fixture) generally don't require permits in California. New circuits, panel work, EV chargers, and service upgrades typically do. We handle the permit process when required.</p></div></div>
            <div class="faq-item fade-up"><button type="button" class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false"><span>Is it safe to do minor electrical work myself?</span><span class="faq-icon"><svg width="11" height="11" viewBox="0 0 12 12" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path d="M6 2v8M2 6h8"/></svg></span></button><div class="faq-answer"><p>California law allows homeowners to do electrical work on their own homes (with permits where required). However, mistakes in wiring can be invisible until they cause a fire or injury. Given the risk and insurance implications, licensed work is almost always the safer choice.</p></div></div>
            <div class="faq-item fade-up"><button type="button" class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false"><span>Why does my breaker keep tripping?</span><span class="faq-icon"><svg width="11" height="11" viewBox="0 0 12 12" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path d="M6 2v8M2 6h8"/></svg></span></button><div class="faq-answer"><p>Common causes: the circuit is overloaded (too many devices on one circuit), the breaker itself is failing, or there's a wiring fault somewhere on the circuit. Repeatedly resetting a tripping breaker without finding the cause is dangerous. A licensed electrician can diagnose this in one visit.</p></div></div>
            <div class="faq-item fade-up"><button type="button" class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false"><span>How long does an EV charger installation take?</span><span class="faq-icon"><svg width="11" height="11" viewBox="0 0 12 12" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path d="M6 2v8M2 6h8"/></svg></span></button><div class="faq-answer"><p>Most Level 2 EV charger installations take 2–4 hours. If a panel upgrade is needed first, add additional time. We assess your panel capacity before quoting, so there are no surprises about whether additional work is needed.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-col">
            <div class="faq-item fade-up"><button type="button" class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false"><span>What are signs my electrical panel needs upgrading?</span><span class="faq-icon"><svg width="11" height="11" viewBox="0 0 12 12" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path d="M6 2v8M2 6h8"/></svg></span></button><div class="faq-answer"><p>Signs include: frequently tripped breakers, flickering lights, burning smell from the panel, breakers that feel warm, or a panel under 150 amps if you're adding an EV charger or major appliance. Any panel over 25–30 years old should be inspected.</p></div></div>
            <div class="faq-item fade-up"><button type="button" class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false"><span>Are your electricians licensed in California?</span><span class="faq-icon"><svg width="11" height="11" viewBox="0 0 12 12" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path d="M6 2v8M2 6h8"/></svg></span></button><div class="faq-answer"><p>Yes. Every electrician we send holds a valid California C-10 Electrical Contractor license and carries liability insurance. You can verify their license number on the CSLB website if you'd like.</p></div></div>
            <div class="faq-item fade-up"><button type="button" class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false"><span>Can you install ceiling fans without existing fan wiring?</span><span class="faq-icon"><svg width="11" height="11" viewBox="0 0 12 12" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path d="M6 2v8M2 6h8"/></svg></span></button><div class="faq-answer"><p>Yes. Rooms with a standard light fixture can be upgraded for ceiling fan use. This typically requires replacing the existing electrical box with a fan-rated box and, depending on the fan controls desired, may require running a second wire for separate fan/light switching.</p></div></div>
            <div class="faq-item fade-up"><button type="button" class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false"><span>What's a GFCI outlet and where is it required?</span><span class="faq-icon"><svg width="11" height="11" viewBox="0 0 12 12" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path d="M6 2v8M2 6h8"/></svg></span></button><div class="faq-answer"><p>A GFCI (Ground Fault Circuit Interrupter) outlet cuts power instantly if it detects a ground fault — preventing electrocution near water. California code requires GFCI protection in kitchens, bathrooms, garages, outdoors, and near any water source. Older homes often lack them entirely.</p></div></div>
            <div class="faq-item fade-up"><button type="button" class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false"><span>What areas do you serve?</span><span class="faq-icon"><svg width="11" height="11" viewBox="0 0 12 12" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path d="M6 2v8M2 6h8"/></svg></span></button><div class="faq-answer"><p>We serve Los Angeles and surrounding areas. Enter your ZIP code in the quote form to confirm electrician availability in your specific area.</p></div></div>
          </div>
        </div>
